.TH ME 1 "2026-04-23" "ME 2.08" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
me \- terminal text editor (microEmacs variant)
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B me
[\fIoptions\fR] [\fIfile\fR ...]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B me
is a terminal-based text editor derived from the public domain microEmacs
by Dave G. Conroy.  It uses Emacs-style key bindings by default and
supports multiple windows, multiple buffers, PCRE regular expressions,
Blowfish-encrypted files, keystroke macros, and a word-wrap mode with
auto-reflow.
.PP
The editor can also be invoked as
.B v
(a symlink), which starts in vi view mode (read-only navigation).
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \-h
Print a brief help message and exit.
.TP
.B \-v
Start in vi/view mode (read-only navigation keys).
.TP
.B \-V
Print the version string and exit.
.TP
.B \-w
Enable word-wrap mode for all buffers on startup.
.TP
.B \-m
Enable mouse reporting (xterm-compatible terminals).
.SH CONCEPTS
.SS Point and Mark
The
.I point
is the current cursor position.  The
.I mark
is a saved position set with \fB^@\fR or \fBM-Space\fR.  The text between
the mark and the point is the
.I region
and can be copied, cut, or processed as a unit.
.SS Buffers and Windows
Each file is loaded into a named
.IR buffer .
Multiple buffers can be open simultaneously.  The screen can be split into
.I windows
each displaying a different buffer.  Changes in one window to a buffer are
immediately visible in any other window showing that buffer.
.SS The Kill Buffer
Killed (cut) text is saved in the
.I kill buffer
and can be yanked back with \fB^Y\fR.  Consecutive kill operations append
to the same kill buffer entry.
.SS Numeric Argument
.B ^U
introduces a numeric argument for the following command.
Digits and a leading
.B \-
can be typed after \fB^U\fR.  Without digits, \fB^U\fR multiplies
the argument by four (default argument is 4).
.SH KEY BINDINGS
Keys are written using the following notation:
.TP
\fB^X\fR
Control-X
.TP
\fBM\-x\fR
Meta-x (typically Alt+x or ESC then x)
.TP
\fB^X^Y\fR
Control-X prefix followed by Control-Y
.TP
\fB^Xy\fR
Control-X prefix followed by y
.SS Cursor Movement
.TP
.B ^A
Go to the beginning of the current line.
.TP
.B ^E
Go to the end of the current line.
.TP
.B ^B
Move backward (left) one character.
.TP
.B ^F
Move forward (right) one character.
.TP
.B ^P
Move to the previous line.
.TP
.B ^N
Move to the next line.
.TP
.B M\-b
Move backward one word.
.TP
.B M\-f
Move forward one word.
.TP
.B M\-<
Go to the beginning of the buffer.
.TP
.B M\->
Go to the end of the buffer.
.TP
.B M\-n
Go to a specific line number (prompts for line number).
.TP
.B ^X=
Display the current line number and column.
.TP
.B M\-!
Reposition the current line within the window.
.SS Paging
.TP
.B ^V
Scroll forward one page.
.TP
.B ^C
Scroll backward one page.
.TP
.B ^X^N
Scroll the window down one line (cursor stays on screen).
.TP
.B ^X^P
Scroll the window up one line.
.SS Basic Editing
.TP
.B ^M
Insert a newline.
.TP
.B ^I
Insert a tab (soft tab if softtabs is set).
.TP
.B ^J, ^O
Insert newline with current indentation (indent).
.TP
.B ^D
Delete the character at the point (forward delete).
.TP
.B ^H, DEL
Delete the character before the point (backward delete).
.TP
.B ^Q
Quote the next character (insert it literally, ignoring its binding).
.TP
.B ^T
Twiddle (swap) the two characters at the point.
.TP
.B ^K
Kill (cut) from the point to the end of the line.
Killing an empty line kills the newline.  Repeated \fB^K\fR commands
append to the kill buffer.
.TP
.B M\-d
Delete forward one word.
.TP
.B M\-^H, M\-DEL
Delete backward one word.
.TP
.B ^X^M, ^X^O
Delete blank lines around the point.
.TP
.B M\-8
Convert 8-bit characters to their nearest 7-bit ASCII equivalents.
Covers Windows-1252 smart quotes, em dashes, ellipses, and Latin-1
accented characters.  Reports the number of replacements made.
.SS Case Conversion
.TP
.B M\-u
Uppercase the word at or after the point.
.TP
.B M\-l
Lowercase the word at or after the point.
.TP
.B M\-C
Capitalize (uppercase first letter) the word.
.TP
.B ^X^U
Uppercase the marked region.
.TP
.B ^X^L
Lowercase the marked region.
.SS Mark and Region
.TP
.B ^@, M\-Space
Set the mark at the current point.
.TP
.B ^X^X, ^Xx
Swap the point and the mark.
.SS Kill, Copy, and Yank
.TP
.B M\-x
Cut the marked region (kill region); text goes to the kill buffer.
.TP
.B ^X^W
Kill (wipe) the marked region; same as M\-x.
.TP
.B M\-c, M\-w
Copy the marked region to the kill buffer without deleting it.
.TP
.B ^Y, M\-v
Yank (paste) the kill buffer contents back at the point.
.SS Search and Replace
.TP
.B ^S
Forward incremental search.  Type the search string; \fB^S\fR again
finds the next occurrence.  \fB^G\fR or \fBRET\fR exits.
PCRE regular expressions are supported.
.TP
.B ^R
Reverse incremental search.
.TP
.B M\-r
Query replace.  Prompts for a search string and a replacement string,
then steps through each match asking: \fBSpace\fR or \fBy\fR to
replace and advance, \fBn\fR to skip, \fB.\fR to replace and stop,
\fB!\fR to replace all remaining without prompting, \fB^G\fR to abort.
.SS Files
.TP
.B ^X^V
Visit (open) a file.  Prompts for a filename and loads it into a buffer.
.TP
.B ^X^F
Read a file into the current buffer, replacing its contents.
.TP
.B ^X^S
Save the current buffer to its associated file.
.TP
.B M\-^W
Write the buffer to a file (prompts for filename).
.TP
.B ^X^R
Change the filename associated with the current buffer (does not write).
.TP
.B ^X^I
Insert a file at the point.
.TP
.B M\-^R
Reread the current file from disk, discarding unsaved changes.
.TP
.B M\-^N
Switch to the next file on the command-line argument list.
.SS Buffers
.TP
.B ^X^B
List all open buffers in a temporary window.
.TP
.B ^Xb, M\-B
Switch to a named buffer (prompts for name).
.TP
.B ^Xk
Kill (close) a buffer.  Prompts if the buffer has unsaved changes.
.TP
.B M\-p
Pack the buffer: remove trailing whitespace from every line.
.SS Windows
.TP
.B ^X1
Collapse to a single window showing the current buffer.
.TP
.B ^X2
Split the current window into two windows.
.TP
.B ^Xn
Move to the next window.
.TP
.B ^Xp
Move to the previous window.
.TP
.B ^Xg
Grow (enlarge) the current window by one line.
.TP
.B ^X^Z
Shrink the current window by one line.
.SS Macros
A keystroke macro records a sequence of keystrokes that can be replayed.
.TP
.B ^X(, ^X[, M\-[
Start recording a macro.
.TP
.B ^X), ^X], M\-]
Stop recording the macro.
.TP
.B ^Xe
Execute the recorded macro once (or N times with a numeric argument).
.TP
.B M\-.
Assign the recorded macro to the
.I dot macro
slot, which is then invoked by the
.B .
key.
.TP
.B .
Execute the dot macro if one is set; otherwise insert a literal period.
.SS Word Wrap
.TP
.B M\-W
Toggle word-wrap mode for the current buffer.  In wrap mode, inserting
past the right margin automatically wraps the current word to the next
line.
.TP
.B M\-q
Reflow (fill) the current paragraph to the right margin.
.TP
.B M\-Q
Reflow all paragraphs in the buffer.
.TP
.B ^Xf
Set the right margin.  With no argument, sets it to the current column;
with a numeric argument (e.g., \fB^U 72 ^Xf\fR), sets it to that value.
.TP
.B M\-i
Set the left indent for auto-wrap.
.SS Variables
.TP
.B M\-s
Set a variable.  Prompts for a variable name and a new value.
Entering an empty name displays all current variable values.
Entering a name only (no value) displays the current value.
See
.SM VARIABLES
below for the list of settable variables.
.SS Encryption
.TP
.B M\-E
Encrypt the current buffer.  Prompts for a passphrase.  The buffer is
encrypted in memory using Blowfish CBC; save with \fB^X^S\fR to write
the encrypted file.
.TP
.B M\-D
Decrypt the current buffer.  Prompts for the passphrase.  Reports an
error if the passphrase is wrong.
.SS Miscellaneous
.TP
.B ^G
Abort the current command or operation.
.TP
.B ^L
Redraw the screen.
.TP
.B ^Z
Suspend the editor and spawn a subshell (resume with \fBexit\fR or \fBfg\fR).
.TP
.B ^X!
Spawn a subshell without suspending the editor.
.TP
.B ^X|
Pipe the current buffer through a shell command.  The command output
replaces the buffer.  Append
.BI @ buffername
to the command to send output to a named buffer instead.
.TP
.B M\-m
Toggle mouse support on or off.
.TP
.B M\-h
Display all key bindings in a temporary buffer.
.TP
.B M\-?
Explain the function bound to the next key pressed.
.TP
.B M\-^[
Toggle vi mode on or off.
.TP
.B M\-V
Enter vi view (read-only) mode.
.TP
.B ^X^C
Quit.  Prompts if any buffers have unsaved changes.
.SH VARIABLES
Variables are set with
.B M\-s
or via the
.B set
directive in the init file.
.TP
.BR rmarg ", " rm
Right margin column for word wrap and paragraph fill (default: 77).
.TP
.BR lmarg ", " lm
Left margin column for word wrap and indent (default: 0).
.TP
.BR tabsize ", " t
Tab stop width (default: 4).
.TP
.BR softtabs ", " T
When non-zero, tabs are inserted as spaces to the next tab stop
(default: 1).
.SH INIT FILE
On startup
.B me
reads
.IR ~/.me/init .
Lines beginning with
.B #
are comments.  Blank lines are ignored.
.SS Syntax
.TP
\fBset\fR \fIname\fR \fIvalue\fR
Set a variable (see
.SM VARIABLES
above).
.TP
\fBbind\fR \fIkey\fR \fIcommand\fR
Rebind a key to a built-in command by name.  Command names match the
names shown by \fBM\-h\fR.  If a binding shadows a built-in, a warning
is displayed on startup.
.TP
\fBbind\fR \fIkey\fR \fB|\fR \fIshell command\fR
Bind a key so that pressing it pipes the current buffer through the
given shell command (same semantics as \fB^X|\fR).
.TP
\fBmacro\fR \fIname\fR
Load the named macro file from
.I ~/.me/macros/
as the keystroke macro on startup.
.SS Key Name Syntax
.TP
.B M\-x
Meta+x
.TP
.B C\-x, ^x
Control+x
.TP
.B C\-Xx, ^Xx
Control-X prefix then x
.TP
.B C\-X^x, ^X^x
Control-X prefix then Control+x
.SS Example
.nf
set rm 72
bind M-s | sort
macro daily
.fi
.SH ENCRYPTION
Encrypted files begin with the magic prefix
.B #ME1.42$
and use Blowfish CBC with a key derived from the passphrase via MD5.
The standalone utility
.B crypt
uses the same format and can encrypt or decrypt files without opening
the editor.
.SH VI MODE
Vi mode provides read-only navigation using familiar vi keys.  It is
entered with \fB\-v\fR on the command line, by invoking the editor as
.BR v ,
or with \fBM\-^\e[\fR (Meta-Escape) or \fBM\-V\fR while editing.
.PP
In vi mode the following additional bindings are active:
.TP
.BR h ", " l
Move left or right one character.
.TP
.BR j ", " k
Move down or up one line.
.TP
.BR n ", " ^V
Scroll forward one page.
.TP
.BR m ", " u ", " b ", " ^C
Scroll backward one page.
.TP
.B x
Delete the character at the point (forward delete).
.TP
.B A
Append at end of line (leaves vi mode).
.TP
.B s
Substitute: delete current character and leave vi mode for insert.
.TP
.B /
Forward search.
.TP
.B \e
Backward search.
.TP
.BR i ", " ^G
Leave vi mode and return to normal editing.
.TP
.B q
Quit.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I ~/.me/init
User configuration file.
.TP
.I ~/.me/kbm_file
Persisted keystroke macro (restored on next startup).
.TP
.I ~/.me/macros/
Directory of named keystroke macro files.
.TP
.I ,,filename
Backup copy of a file, created in the same directory as the original
before the file is written.  (Backup creation is always on when running
as root.)
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR crypt (1),
.BR pcre (3)
